Introduction¶

The aim of this project is to build a Convolutional Neural Network that is able to discriminate images containing fire from images that do not contain any fire source. To face this challenge we collected several images containing fire sources and many images that do not contain any fire source. All these images were divided into two folders, the first grouping all the images that contain fire and the second grouping all the images that do not contain fire. We decided also to preprocess all these images to enhance the accuracy of our classifier. For that reason we implemented the following steps:

  • We resized all the images for consistency reasons,
  • We converted the background and not useful features in black and white,
  • We mantained and highlighted only frequencies of reds, oranges and yellows,
  • We randomly rotaded the images to prevent patterns,
  • We normalized the color channels as follows:
    T.Normalize( mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
              std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225] )


As for as the construction of the model we decided to use the PyTorch framework, following a try, evaluate and improve method. We started from a simple idea and after each evaluation step of the model we tried to modify and implement new solutions to obtain the best solution possible.

# The aim of this function is to pre-process the images and store them into tensors
# on the chosen device

def processing_image_Pytorch(filepath):

  img = cv2.imread(filepath)

  img = cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_RGB2BGR)
  img = cv2.resize(img,(256,256)) 

  img_bw  = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
  img_bw = cv2.resize(img_bw, (256,256))
  img_bw = cv2.merge([img_bw,img_bw,img_bw])

  lower = np.array([200,0,0], dtype="uint8")
  upper = np.array([255,255,129], dtype= "uint8")

  mask = cv2.inRange(img, lower, upper)
  output = cv2.bitwise_and(img, img, mask = mask) 

  mask = cv2.bitwise_not(mask)
  background = cv2.bitwise_or(img_bw,img_bw,mask =  mask)

  opencvOutput = cv2.bitwise_or(output, background)

  pil_img = Image.fromarray(opencvOutput)

  preprocess = T.Compose([
   T.Resize(256),
   T.CenterCrop(256),
   T.RandomHorizontalFlip(p=0.5),
   T.ToTensor(),
   T.Normalize(
       mean=[0.485, 0.456, 0.406],
       std=[0.229, 0.224, 0.225]
     )
  ])

  x = preprocess(pil_img)
  x_g = x.to(device)
  return x_g


# This functions create the X and y datasets for training and test, pre-processing 
# each image and storing them into tensors on the chosen device
def create_df_Pytorch(dataframe):

  X = []
  for i in range(len(dataframe.values[:,0])):
    X.append(processing_image_Pytorch(dataframe.values[i,0]))
  X = torch.stack(X)

  y = torch.from_numpy(np.array(dataframe.values[:,1], dtype="int8")) #.reshape(len(dataframe.values[:,1]),1))
  y_g = y.to(device)

  return X, y_g


# Simple post processing visualization
def processed(path):

    img = cv2.imread(path)
    img = cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_RGB2BGR)
    img = cv2.resize(img, (256,256))
    img_bw = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    img_bw = cv2.merge([img_bw,img_bw,img_bw])

    ##--define color range scale (BGR)
    lower = np.array([200,0,0], dtype="uint8")
    upper = np.array([255,255,129], dtype= "uint8")

    ##--mask creation
    mask = cv2.inRange(img, lower, upper)
    output = cv2.bitwise_and(img, img, mask = mask) 

    ##--application of inverted mask on the bw version of image
    mask = cv2.bitwise_not(mask)
    background = cv2.bitwise_or(img_bw,img_bw,mask =  mask)

    ##--change back in final (join the images background with the fire image)
    opencvOutput = cv2.bitwise_or(output, background)

    plt.imshow(opencvOutput);

Model implementation¶

In [12]:
# Best model

class Net(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Net, self).__init__()

        # convolutional layer
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, 8, stride = 1, padding = 3)
        # max pooling layer
        self.pool1 = nn.MaxPool2d(8, 8)

        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 128, 8, stride = 1, padding = 3)
        self.pool2 = nn.MaxPool2d(4, 4)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.2)

        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(128, 256, 4, stride = 1, padding = 2)
        self.pool3 = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)

        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(256 * 4 * 4, 512)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(512, 84)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(84, 2)

        self.softmax = nn.LogSoftmax(dim=1)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        # add sequence of convolutional and max pooling layers
        x = self.pool1(F.relu(self.conv1(x)))
        x = self.pool2(F.relu(self.conv2(x)))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.pool3(F.relu(self.conv3(x)))
        #print("x before",x.shape) #check the shape
        x = x.view(-1, 256 * 4 * 4)
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.dropout(F.relu(self.fc2(x)))
        x = self.softmax(self.fc3(x))
        return x
        
model = Net().to(device)

Specific functions for training the model¶

In [15]:
# This function adjust the learning rate after a pre-determined number of epochs
# where we noticed bouncing behaviors around local minimum
def adjust_learning_rate(epoch):

    lr = 0.001

    if epoch > 88:
        lr = lr / 100000000
    elif epoch > 80:
        lr = lr / 10000000     
    elif epoch > 72:
        lr = lr / 1000000    
    elif epoch > 50:
        lr = lr / 100000
    elif epoch > 38:
        lr = lr / 10000
    elif epoch > 24:
        lr = lr / 1000
    elif epoch > 10:
        lr = lr / 100
    elif epoch > 6:
        lr = lr / 10

# This function will save the model if the performance at some epoch is the 
# best performance so far
def save_models(epoch):
    torch.save(model.state_dict(), "fire_{}.model".format(epoch))


# This function is used for testing purposes. It is directly called into the 
# training loop where the test_accuracy is needed
def test ():

  test_acc = 0.0
  # iterate over test data

    loss = criterion(outputs, target)#.reshape(len(test_loader),1))

    _, prediction = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
    test_acc += torch.sum(prediction == target.data)

      # Compute the average acc and loss over all 10000 test images
  test_acc = test_acc / len(y_test)

  return test_acc
In [16]:
# Here we store the accuracy and the loss for plotting purposes
test_accur_plot = []
train_accur_plot = []
loss_plot = []

# Actual training loop
def train(num_epochs):
    best_acc = 0.0

    for epoch in range(num_epochs):
        model.train()
        train_acc = 0.0
        train_loss = 0.0
        
        for i, (images, labels) in enumerate(train_loader):
          images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)
          images.requires_grad=True
          # Clear all accumulated gradients
          optimizer.zero_grad()
          # Predict classes using images from the test set
          outputs = model(images)
          # Compute the loss based on the predictions and actual labels
          loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
          # Backpropagate the loss
          loss.backward()

          # Adjust parameters according to the computed gradients
          optimizer.step()

          train_loss += loss.item() * images.size(0)
          _, prediction = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
            
          train_acc += torch.sum(prediction == labels.data)

        # Call the learning rate adjustment function
        adjust_learning_rate(epoch)

        # Compute the average acc and loss over all training images
        train_acc = train_acc / len(y_train)
        train_loss = train_loss / len(y_train)

        global train_accur_plot
        train_accur_plot.append(train_acc.cpu().detach().numpy())
        

        global loss_plot
        loss_plot.append(float(train_loss))
        
        
        # Evaluate on the test set
        test_acc = test()

        global test_accur_plot
        test_accur_plot.append(test_acc.cpu().detach().numpy())
        

        # Save the model if the test acc is greater than our current best
        if test_acc > best_acc:
            save_models(epoch)
            best_acc = test_acc
            print("Chekcpoint saved! -> Epoch {}, Train Accuracy: {} , TrainLoss: {} , Test Accuracy: {}".format(epoch, train_acc, train_loss,test_acc))

        # Print the metrics
        if epoch % 10 == 0:
          print("Epoch {}, Train Accuracy: {} , TrainLoss: {} , Test Accuracy: {}".format(epoch, train_acc, train_loss,test_acc))

    train_accur_plot = np.array(train_accur_plot)
    loss_plot = np.array(loss_plot)
    test_accur_plot = np.array(test_accur_plot)

def print_img(filepath):
  #--Print image with real shapes and colour
  img = cv2.imread(filepath)
  img = cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_RGB2BGR)
  img = cv2.resize(img, (256,256))
  img_bw = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
  img_bw = cv2.merge([img_bw,img_bw,img_bw])

  ##--define color range scale (BGR)
  lower = np.array([200,0,0], dtype="uint8")
  upper = np.array([255,255,129], dtype= "uint8")

  ##--mask creation
  mask = cv2.inRange(img, lower, upper)
  output = cv2.bitwise_and(img, img, mask = mask) 

  ##--application of inverted mask on the bw version of image
  mask = cv2.bitwise_not(mask)
  background = cv2.bitwise_or(img_bw,img_bw,mask =  mask)

  ##--change back in final (join the images background with the fire image)
  opencvOutput = cv2.bitwise_or(output, background)

  ##--Define space for images printing
  fig=plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
  row = 1
  columns = 2

  #--Prediction generation
  img_t = processing_image_Pytorch(filepath)
  img_t = torch.unsqueeze(img_t,0)

  model.eval()
  img_out = model(img_t)
  _, prediction = torch.max(img_out,1)

  #--Result
  if prediction == 0:
    plt.title("No Fire Detected",
              fontdict={'color' : 'grey','weight': 'bold','size': 18})
    plt.axis("off")

    fig.add_subplot(row,columns,1)
    plt.title("Original Image")
    plt.imshow(img)

    fig.add_subplot(row,columns,2)
    plt.title("Processed Image")
    plt.imshow(opencvOutput)
  else:
    plt.title("Warning! Fire detected",
              fontdict={'color' : 'red','weight': 'bold','size': 18})
    plt.axis("off")

    fig.add_subplot(row,columns,1)
    plt.title("Original Image")
    plt.imshow(img)

    fig.add_subplot(row,columns,2)
    plt.title("Processed Image")
    plt.imshow(opencvOutput)

class Net(nn.Module):

        # convolutional layer
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 64, 3)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(64, 32, 3)
        # max pooling layer
        self.pool = nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2)
        # convolutional layer
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, 3)

        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(64*47*47, 128)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(128, 2)

        self.softmax = nn.LogSoftmax(dim=1)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        # add sequence of convolutional and max pooling layers
        x = F.relu(self.conv1(x))
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv2(x)))
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv3(x)))

        #print("x before",x.shape) #check the shape
        x = x.view(-1, 64 * 47 * 47)
        x = self.fc1(x)
        x = self.softmax(self.fc2(x))
        return x

# Model 2

class Net(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(Net, self).__init__()
        # convolutional layer
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(3, 32, 3, stride = 1, padding = 2)
        # max pooling layer
        self.pool = nn.MaxPool2d(4, 4)
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(32, 64, 3, stride = 1, padding = 2)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.2)
        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(64, 32, 3, stride = 1, padding = 2)
        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(32*17*17, 256)
        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(256, 84)
        self.fc3 = nn.Linear(84,2)
        self.softmax = nn.LogSoftmax(dim=1)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        # add sequence of convolutional and max pooling layers
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv1(x)))
        x = F.relu(self.conv2(x))
        x = self.dropout(x)
        x = self.pool(F.relu(self.conv3(x)))
        #print("x before",x.shape) #check the shape
        x = x.view(-1, 32 * 17 * 17)
        x = F.relu(self.fc1(x))
        x = self.dropout(F.relu(self.fc2(x)))
        x = self.softmax(self.fc3(x))
        return x
